answers.body_markdown:
&gt; But exists an bigger issue that is when I register two instances are co-dependant (e.g. An class A that needs a B instance, but the B needs an A instance)

This is a [Code Smell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_smell) that something has been (most likely) designed poorly.  Usually the *best option* is to redesign/refactor the requirements to remove this type of circular dependency.  One of the biggest problems with circular dependencies is the ability for each dependency to call the other in a way that causes each to call a method on the other in a sort of *recursive* way until the system fails with a stack-overflow.

&gt;  I need to implement for a personal project and will apreciate all the advices you can give me.

That being said, there are few ways to do this if it&#39;s *truly needed*.  In my personal opinion, the next best option (after redesign/refactor) is use a deferred/delegate constructor injection.  This might look like:

     // &quot;Func Factory&quot;
     public class A
     {
       private Func&lt;B&gt; _bFactory;
       private B b
       {
         if (_b == null)
         {
          _b = _bFactory();
         }
         return _b;
       }

       public A(Func&lt;B&gt; bFactory)
       {
         _bFactory = bFactory;
       }

       public void SomeMethod()
       {
         b.DoSomething();
       }
     }

or a cleaner solution (IMHO)

     // &quot;Lazy Factory&quot;
     public class A
     {
       private Lazy&lt;B&gt; _b;

       public A(Lazy&lt;B&gt; b)
       {
         _b = b;
       }

